        <h1>SAM Question Bank 2079 - 2079</h1>
        <p><strong>Full Marks:</strong> 60 + 20 + 20</p>
        <p><strong>Pass Marks:</strong> 24 + 8 + 8</p>
        <p><strong>Time:</strong> 3 hours</p>
    <h2>Group A: Answer any Two Questions</h2><h3>Question 1</h3>
<div><p><p>What is transaction in GPSS? Explain about facility in GPSS. Customers arrive at Joey Barbershop one every 15±3 minutes and it takes Joey 18±2 minutes to cut hair of a customer. Create a GPSS model with block diagram for the Barbershop using the concept of facility and run the simulation for 9 hours.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>Transaction Definition:</strong></p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">A transaction in GPSS represents a discrete unit of work or an entity that moves through the simulation model.Transactions are typically used to model the flow of entities, such as customers, products, or orders, through a system.Transactions move through the system by interacting with various GPSS blocks and processes.The simulation model defines how transactions move, wait, and interact with other entities or resources.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>Facility in GPSS</strong></p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">A facility in GPSS refers to a resource or a processing station where transactions can be processed or delayed.Facilities are represented in the simulation model by the &#8220;FACILITY&#8221; block in GPSS.Examples of facilities include machines, servers, or any resource that can process transactions.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">When a transaction needs to use a facility, it requests the facility using the &#8220;SEIZE&#8221; block.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">If the facility is available, the transaction seizes it and begins processing. If the facility is busy, the transaction may have to wait in a queue until the facility becomes available.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>Numerical</strong></p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">SIMULATE</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">GENERATE 15,3            ; Generate customers every 15±3 minutes</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">QUEUE 2                  ; Allow up to 2 customers to queue up if necessary</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">SEIZE 3                  ; Seize the barber facility when available</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">DEPART 2                ; Customer leaves the queue</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">ADVANCE 18,2             ; Customer gets a haircut (18±2 minutes)</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">RELEASE 3               ; Release the barber facility</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">TERMINATE 0             ; End the simulation for each customer</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">GENERATE 540            ; Generate a timer after 9 hours of simulated time</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">TERMINATE 1             ; Shut off the simulation run</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">START 1                 ; Start carrying out the simulation</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">END</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-28139" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/IMG_2843.jpg?resize=1657%2C1715&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="1657" height="1715"></p>
<p><img /></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Why accuracy of analog computer is low? Explain analog computer with suitable example. Differentiate between analog and digital computer.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p style="font-weight: 400;">The accuracy of analog computers is generally considered lower compared to digital computers for several reasons:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Noise and Interference: </strong>Analog signals are susceptible to noise and interference from external sources.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Component Variability: </strong>Analog components, such as resistors, capacitors, and transistors, can exhibit variations in their characteristics due to manufacturing tolerances and aging.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Limited Precision: </strong>Analog signals are continuous and theoretically have an infinite number of possible values within a given range.</li>
</ul>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">Analog Computers:<br />
An analog computer is a type of computing device that represents data using continuous signals. These signals can be electrical, mechanical, or hydraulic in nature. Analog computers are designed to process and manipulate continuous data, making them well-suited for tasks that involve physical quantities and measurements.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">
<strong>Characteristics of Analog Computers:</strong></p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">
<strong>• Continuous Signals:</strong> Analog computers use continuous signals to represent data, allowing for a smooth representation of quantities.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">
<strong>• Precision in Measurement:</strong> Well-suited for tasks involving physical measurements and real-world phenomena.<strong>• Speed:</strong> Analog computers can be faster in processing certain types of tasks compared to digital computers for specific applications.</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">
<strong>Example of Analog Computer:</strong><br />
One example of an analog computer is an analog electronic thermometer. In this device, the position of a mercury column in a glass tube provides a continuous analog representation of temperature.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Difference between Analog and Digital Computers</strong></p>
