<h2>Group B: Answer any Eight Questions</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>Why Confidence interval is needed in the analysis of simulation output. How can we establish a confidence interval?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The confidence interval is the range of possible values for the parameter based on a set of data (e.g. the simulation results.). Confidence interval is needed because:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li> A confidence interval displays the probability that a parameter will fall between a pair of values around the mean.</li>
<li> Confidence intervals measure the degree of uncertainty or certainty in a sampling method.</li>
</ul>
<p>Confidence intervals are based on the premise that the data being produced by the simulation is represented well by a probability model. Suppose the model is the normally distributed with mean , Variance and we have a sample of n size then the confidence interval is given by:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-28140" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/IMG_2844.jpg?resize=1597%2C1455&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="1597" height="1455"></p>
<p>Hence, the estimates between can be accepted for 95% confidence interval.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain the Monte Carlo simulation method. with example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Monte Carlo simulation is a computational technique that uses random sampling to model and analyze complex systems or processes. It relies on the generation of random inputs to explore the behavior of a system, allowing for the estimation of outcomes and the assessment of associated uncertainties. The method is named after the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, known for its games of chance and randomness.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Following are the three important characteristics of Monte-Carlo method:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Its output must generate random samples.</li>
<li> Its input distribution must be known.</li>
<li>Its result must be known while performing an experiment.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-28141" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/12/IMG_2845.jpg?resize=2048%2C1749&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="2048" height="1749"></p>
<p>We use random number generation method to determine the sample points that lie inside or outside the curve.</p>
<p>Let (x0, y0) be an initial guess for the sample point than from a linear congruential method of random number generation:</p>
<p><strong> Xi+1 = (axi+c) mod m </strong></p>
<p><strong>Yi+1 = (ayi+c) mod m </strong></p>
<p>Where a &amp; c are constants, m is the upper limit of generated random number.</p>
<p>If y&lt;=yi then increment n.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Generate ten 3 digit random integers and corresponding randomn variables using Multiplicative Congruential method where a =7, and X0= 22.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Given,</p>
<p>X0 = 22,</p>
<p>a= 7</p>
<p>For three-digit random integers m=1000 We have, For multiplicative congruential method ( c =0) so</p>
<p>Xi+1 = (a Xi ) mod m</p>
<p><strong>The sequence of random integers are calculated as follows:</strong></p>
<p>X0 = 22</p>
<p>R0 = 22/1000 = 0.022</p>
<p>X1 = (a X0) mod m = (7*22) mod 1000 = 15 mod 1000 = 154</p>
<p>R1 = 154/1000 = 0.154</p>
<p>X2 = (a X1) mod m = (7*154) mod 1000 = 1078 mod 1000 = 78</p>
<p>R2 = 78/1000 = 0.078</p>
<p>X3 = (a X2) mod m = (7*78) mod 1000 = 546 mod 1000 = 546</p>
<p>R3 = 546/1000 = 0.546</p>
<p>X4= (a X3 ) mod m = (7*546) mod 1000 = 3822 mod 1000 = 822</p>
<p>R4 = 822/1000 = 0.822</p>
<p>X5= (a X4 ) mod m = (7*822) mod 1000 = 5754 mod 1000 = 754</p>
<p>R5= 754/1000 = 0.754</p>
<p>X6= (a X5) mod m = (7*754) mod 1000 = 5278 mod 1000 = 278</p>
<p>R6 = 278/1000 = 0.278</p>
<p>X7= (a X6) mod m = (7*278) mod 1000 = 1946 mod 1000 = 946</p>
<p>R7 = 946/1000 = 0.946</p>
<p>X8= (a X7) mod m = (7*946) mod 1000 = 6622 mod 1000 = 622</p>
<p>R8 = 622/1000 = 0.622</p>
<p>X9= (a X8) mod m = (7*622) mod 1000 = 4354 mod 1000 = 354</p>
<p>R9 = 354/1000 = 0.354</p>
<p>X10 = (a X9) mod m = (7*354) mod 1000 = 2478 mod 1000 = 478</p>
<p>R10 = 478/1000 = 0.478</p>
<p>Therefore,</p>
<p>The sequence of three digit random integers are 022, 154, 078, 546, 822, 754, 278, 946, 622, 354, 478 The sequence of random numbers are 0.022, 0.154, 0.078, 0. 546, 0.822, 0.754, 0.278, 0.946, 0.622, 0.354, 0.478</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>“Building a model right” and “Building a right model”. Are both statements same?Discuss the importance of V&V</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p style="font-weight: 400;">The statements &#8220;Building a model right&#8221; and &#8220;Building a right model&#8221; may sound similar, but they convey slightly different meanings.</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>&#8220;Building a model right&#8221;:</strong> This statement suggests the emphasis on the process of constructing a model correctly, adhering to best practices, following appropriate methodologies, and ensuring that the implementation aligns with the intended design. It focuses on the correctness of the development process rather than specifically referring to the characteristics or quality of the model itself.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>&#8220;Building a right model&#8221;: </strong>This statement puts more emphasis on the outcome – the model itself. It suggests the importance of constructing a model that is appropriate for the problem at hand, effectively addresses the objectives, and produces reliable and meaningful results. It highlights the need for selecting the right algorithms, features, and parameters to achieve the desired performance.</li>
</ul>
<p style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>The importance of Verification and Validation (V&amp;V) in the context of building models:</strong></p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;">Verification and validation are crucial processes in the development lifecycle of models, especially in fields like software engineering and machine learning. These processes help ensure that the model is not only built correctly but also that it is the right model for the intended purpose. Here&#8217;s a breakdown of their importance:</p>
<p style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>Verification:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Ensuring correctness: Verification involves checking that the model is implemented correctly according to its design specifications..</li>
<li>Detecting errors early: Early identification of errors or issues in the development process can save time and resources by preventing the propagation of defects throughout the model&#8217;s lifecycle.</li>
</ul>
<p style="font-weight: 400;"><strong>Validation:</strong></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Ensuring effectiveness: Validation is concerned with determining whether the model fulfills its intended purpose and whether it produces accurate and reliable results.</li>
<li>Mitigating risks: Validation helps identify and address potential risks and uncertainties associated with the model.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
