<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>What is markov chain? Explain with example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>If the future states of a process are independent of the past and depend only on the present, the process is called a Markov process. A discrete state Markov process is called a Markov chain. A Markov Chain is a random process with the property that the next state depends only on the current state.</p>
<p>Markov chains are used to analyze trends and predict the future. (Weather, stock market, genetics, product success, etc.</p>
<p><strong>Formally,</strong></p>
<p>A Markov chain is a sequence of random variables X<sub>1</sub>, X<sub>2</sub>, X<sub>3</sub>, &#8230; with the Markov property, namely that, given the present state, the future and past states are independent.</p>
<p>\(P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i_n, x_{n-1} = i_{n-1}, . . ., x_0 = i_0) = P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i_n)\)</p>
<p>The conditional probability above gives us the probability that a process in state i<sub>n</sub> at time n moves to i<sub>n+1</sub> at time n + 1. We call this the transition probability for the Markov chain. If the transition probability does not depend on the time n, we have a stationary Markov chain, with transition probabilities</p>
<p>\(P_{ij} = P(X_{n+1} = j|X_n = i)\)</p>
<p>Now we can write down the whole Markov chain as a matrix P:</p>
<p>\(P = \begin{bmatrix}<br />
P_11 &amp; P_12 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_1n\\<br />
P_21 &amp; P_22 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_2n\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
. &amp; . &amp; . &amp; .\\<br />
P_n1 &amp; P_n2 &amp; &#8230;. &amp; P_nn\\<br />
\end{bmatrix}\)</p>
<p>Example:</p>
<p>Weather Problem:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>raining today  ⇒ 40 % rain tomorrow</li>
</ul>
<p>⇒ 60 % no rain tomorrow</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>not raining today  ⇒ 20 % rain tomorrow</li>
</ul>
<p>⇒ 80 % no rain tomorrow</p>
<p>What will be the probability if today is not raining then not rain the day after tomorrow?</p>
<p><i>Markov chain diagram:</i></p>
<p><img data-recalc-dims="1" loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-10953 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/01/download-2.png?resize=334%2C145&#038;ssl=1" alt="" width="334" height="145"></p>
<p>\(P^2 = \begin{pmatrix}0.4 &amp; 0.6 \\ 0.2 &amp; 0.8\end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}0.4 &amp; 0.6 \\ 0.2 &amp; 0.8\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>\(= \begin{pmatrix}0.16 + 0.12 &amp; 0.24 + 0.48 \\ 0.08 + 0.16 &amp; 0.12 + 0.64\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>\(= \begin{pmatrix}0.28 &amp; 0.72 \\ 0.24 &amp; 0.76\end{pmatrix}\)</p>
<p>Thus, the probability of not being rainy the day after tomorrow is 0.76.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Explain basic characteristics of Queueing System</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A queuing system is a mathematical model that represents the waiting lines or queues in various real-world scenarios where entities (such as customers, tasks, or requests) arrive, wait for service, and then depart. Queuing theory is a branch of applied probability that helps analyze and optimize such systems. Here are the basic characteristics of a queuing system:</p>
<p><strong>Arrival Process:</strong></p>
<p>• Arrival Rate (λ): Represents the average number of entities arriving at the queue per unit time.</p>
<p>• Inter-Arrival Time Distribution: Describes the time intervals between consecutive arrivals.</p>
<p><strong>Service Process:</strong></p>
<p>• Service Rate (μ): Indicates the average number of entities served by the system per unit time.</p>
<p>• Service Time Distribution: Describes the time it takes to serve a single entity.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Queue Discipline:</strong></p>
<p>• FIFO (First-In-First-Out): The entity that arrives first is the first to be served.</p>
<p>• LIFO (Last-In-First-Out): The entity that arrives last is the first to be served.</p>
<p>• Priority Queues: Entities are served based on assigned priorities.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Queue Length:</strong></p>
<p>• Number of Servers: The number of servers determines how many entities can be served simultaneously.</p>
<p>• Queue Capacity: Represents the maximum number of entities the queue can hold.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Service Discipline:</strong></p>
<p>• Single Server: Only one entity is served at a time.</p>
<p>• Multiple Servers: Multiple entities can be served simultaneously.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Describe dynamic physical model in detail with the help of suitable example.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>A dynamic physical model is a representation of a system that evolves over time, capturing the changes and interactions among its components. This type of model is used to simulate and analyze the dynamic behavior of a system as it progresses through time. It often involves differential equations or difference equations to describe the rate of change of variables over time.</p>
<p>Example: A pendulum</p>
<p>A pendulum is a simple example of a dynamic physical system. It consists of a mass attached to a pivot point by a string. The pendulum swings back and forth under the influence of gravity.</p>
<p>The motion of the pendulum can also be modeled by the following differential equation:</p>
<p>θ̈ + (g/L) * sin(θ) = 0</p>
<p>where:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>θ̈ is the second derivative of θ with respect to time</li>
<li>L is the length of the pendulum</li>
</ul>
<p>This equation states that the second derivative of the angle of the pendulum is proportional to the negative of the sine of the angle and the acceleration due to gravity divided by the length of the pendulum.</p>
<p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li>They can be used to predict the behavior of systems before they are built or tested.</li>
<li> They can be used to understand the behavior of systems that are too complex to be studied experimentally.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes:</p>
<p>a.Hypothesis testing</p>
<p>b.Stationary poission process</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>a.Hypothesis testing </strong></p>
<p>Hypothesis testing is a statistical method used to make inferences about a population based on a sample of data. It involves formulating two competing hypotheses, the null hypothesis (H0) and the alternative hypothesis (H1), and then using sample data to assess the evidence against the null hypothesis.</p>
<p>Here are the key steps in hypothesis testing:</p>
<p>Formulate Hypotheses:</p>
<p><strong>• Null Hypothesis (H0):</strong> Represents a default or status quo assumption.</p>
<p>It often states that there is no effect or no difference.</p>
<p><strong>• Alternative Hypothesis (H1):</strong> Represents the opposite of the null hypothesis, suggesting an effect or a difference.</p>
<p><strong>Select Significance Level (α):</strong> The significance level, often denoted by α (alpha), represents the probability of rejecting the null hypothesis</p>
<p>After that test the calculated value with significance and decide accept or reject the hypothesis.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>b.Stationary poisson process</strong></p>
<p>A stationary Poisson process is a type of stochastic process that models the occurrence of rare events over time, where events happen randomly and independently. The term &#8220;stationary&#8221; in this context refers to the fact that the statistical properties of the process do not change over time. The Poisson process is named after the French mathematician Siméon Denis Poisson, who introduced it.</p>
<p><strong>Characteristics of a Stationary Poisson Process:</strong></p>
<p><strong>• Event Occurrence:</strong> The process models the occurrence of events in continuous time, such as the arrival of customers at a service point, the decay of radioactive particles, or the arrival of messages in a communication system.</p>
<p><strong>• Independence:</strong> Events occur independently of each other. The occurrence of an event in one time interval does not affect the probability of an event occurring in another interval.</p>
<p><strong>• Constant Rate:</strong>  The events occur at a constant average rate, denoted by λ. The rate represents the average number of events per unit of time.</p>
<p><strong>• Stationarity:</strong> The process is stationary, which means that its statistical properties, such as the average rate of events and the distribution of inter-arrival times, do not change over time.</p>
<p><strong>• Inter-Arrival Times:</strong> The time between consecutive events, known as inter-arrival times, follows an exponential distribution with a mean of 1/λ.</p>
</div>
</body></html>